{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Request payload always includes the full taxonomy label list.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at the module boundary where taxonomy data is handed to the API client/request builder, not just a single pure function. A fake/stub transport can catch missing/partial labels, so real OS/network/subprocess is not required (disqualifies System). Correctness does not depend on model judgment/output quality (disqualifies Agentic/Workflow).","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub API client that records outbound payload. Invoke classification with a known taxonomy and assert the sent request contains every valid label exactly as configured.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Unknown provider label is mapped to \"unknown\".","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic normalization/validation logic: given an out-of-taxonomy label, return \"unknown\". No real module interaction, infra, or model output quality is needed. Behavior text focuses on value mapping, which disqualifies higher levels.","test_description":"Call the normalization/response-mapping function with taxonomy [legal, technical, financial, other] and raw label \"medical\"; assert final result is \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Normalization is deterministic for identical raw API responses.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is explicitly about deterministic transformation of identical inputs to identical outputs. This is a pure local function/property test target; infrastructure and live model calls are unnecessary, disqualifying Integration/System/Agentic/Workflow.","test_description":"Run normalization twice (or property-test many times) on the same raw response fixture and assert identical final label each time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.0,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Repeated live calls are label-consistent unless provider response changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live API calls and consistency of returned labels, which depends on real model/provider behavior and possible non-determinism. Mocks would hide this class of failure. It is not Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Against the real provider, submit the same document+taxonomy N times under controlled settings, record provider raw outputs and final labels, and assert label changes only when provider response content differs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Token budget policy is enforced before dispatch (truncate/reject).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure usually appears at handoff between tokenizer/budget policy and dispatch gate (request should not be sent when over budget unless truncated per policy). A wired module test with stub client verifies pre-dispatch enforcement. No real OS/network needed (disqualifies System), and no dependence on model output quality (disqualifies Agentic/Workflow).","test_description":"Configure a small budget, pass an over-budget document, and use a stub API client to assert either: (a) request was truncated to policy-compliant size before send, or (b) send was blocked/rejected per policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.56,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for typical input stays within configured budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real AI provider call and real usage metadata; stubs can always be made to pass and would hide mismatches between local budgeting and provider accounting. Although assertion is deterministic, execution depends on live AI API behavior, so Agentic is the safer minimum over Integration/System.","test_description":"Run classification on representative documents against the real provider and assert reported usage tokens per call are <= configured budget; fail if provider usage exceeds budget despite local enforcement.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.64,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"On rate-limit signal, module waits and retries instead of surfacing immediate error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is in retry orchestration across classifier module and API client (status interpretation, backoff, second attempt). A controlled stub returning rate-limit then success exposes real failures without real network/OS, disqualifying System. No dependence on model decision quality, disqualifying Agentic/Workflow.","test_description":"Use a stub API client that returns a rate-limit response first, then a valid classification. Assert classifier delays/retries and ultimately returns success, and does not immediately return an error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
